```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <math.h>

void calcStats(int arr[], int n) {
    float sum = 0.0, mean, std_dev = 0.0;
    float skewness = 0.0, kurtosis = 0.0;
    int i;

    for(i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        sum += arr[i];
    }

    mean = sum/n;

    for(i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        std_dev += pow(arr[i] - mean, 2);
    }

    std_dev = sqrt(std_dev/n);

    if(std_dev != 0) { // check to avoid division by zero
        for(i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            skewness += pow((arr[i] - mean) / std_dev, 3);
            kurtosis += pow((arr[i] - mean) / std_dev, 4);
        }

        skewness /= n;
        kurtosis = kurtosis/n - 3;
    }

    printf("Mean: %f\n", mean);
    printf("Skewness: %f\n", skewness);
    printf("Kurtosis: %f\n", kurtosis);
}

int main() {
    int nums[] = {9, 3, 4, 0, 6, 7, 1, 8, 5, 2};
    int n = sizeof(nums) / sizeof(nums[0]);

    calcStats(nums, n);

    return 0;
}
```

The `calcStats` function calculates the mean and standard deviation of the given array. To avoid division by zero, it checks if the standard deviation is not zero before proceeding to calculate skewness and kurtosis. For skewness, if the value is greater than 0, it indicates a positively skewed distribution; if it is less than 0, it indicates a negatively skewed distribution; and if it equals 0, it indicates a normal distribution. For kurtosis, if the value is greater than 0, it indicates a leptokurtic distribution; if it is less than 0, it indicates a platykurtic distribution; and if it equals 0, it indicates a mesokurtic distribution.

The `main` function initializes the array `nums` and calculates its size. It then calls the `calcStats` function with the array and size as arguments.

