Sure! Here's a JavaScript code snippet using Vue.js and axios that accomplishes what you're looking for:

```javascript
new Vue({
    el: '#app',
    data: {
        buttons: []
    },
    async created() {
        try {
            const response = await axios.get("/api/button");
            this.buttons = response.data;
        } catch (error) {
            console.error("An error occurred while fetching button data", error);
        }
    },
    mounted() {
        let buttonElements = document.querySelectorAll('.button-element');

        buttonElements.forEach((buttonElement, index) => {
            this.$set(buttonElement, 'data', this.buttons[index]);
        });
    }
});
```

Let me explain the code to you:

- `el: '#app'` - This line attaches the Vue instance to the DOM element with the id "app".
- `axios.get("/api/button")` - This line fetches the button data from the API endpoint "/api/button" using a GET request.
- `async/await` - These keywords allow you to write asynchronous code in a more synchronous manner. The `async` keyword before the `created` function declaration indicates that the function is asynchronous and will always return a promise. The `await` keyword is used to wait for the completion of a promise before proceeding to the next line of code.
- `this.$set(object, propertyName, value)` - This method is used to add a property to a reactive object in Vue.js. It ensures that the new property is also reactive, meaning any changes to it will trigger reactivity.

In the `created` lifecycle hook, we send a GET request to the API endpoint using axios. Since `axios.get()` returns a promise, we use `await` to wait for the promise to resolve. Once the data is fetched, it is saved into the `buttons` property of our Vue instance's `data` object.

In the `mounted` lifecycle hook, we select all the elements with the class "button-element" using `document.querySelectorAll('.button-element')`. Then, we iterate over the selected elements using `forEach` and update each button's `data` attribute with the corresponding item from the fetched data. To ensure that the new `data` property is reactive, we use Vue's `this.$set()` method, passing in the button element, the name of the property to be added ("data"), and the value of the new property.

