I am working on a project that involves Rust and WebAssembly using the "wasm32-unknown-unknown" target. I have a function in my Rust code that returns a `Vec<i32>` and I can successfully call it from JavaScript. However, when I try to modify the code to return a `Vec<Vec<i32>>`, it doesn't work as expected. I have provided the code for both the working and non-working versions below. Can someone please help me understand what I am doing wrong?

```rust
#[no_mangle]
pub extern "C" fn calc_vector() -> usize {
    unsafe {
        vec_len = 0;
    }

    let mut data: Vec<i32> = Vec::new();

    for i in 0..1000 {
        data.push(i);
    }

    unsafe {
        vec_len = data.len();
    }

    data.as_mut_ptr() as usize
}

#[no_mangle]
pub extern "C" fn calc_vector_in_vector() -> usize {
    unsafe {
        vec_len = 0;
        elements_in_vect = 0;
    }

    let mut outer_vec: Vec<*mut i32> = Vec::new();
    let mut inner_vec: Vec<i32> = Vec::new();

    for i in 0..100 {
        inner_vec.push(i);
        unsafe {
            elements_in_vect += 1;
        }
    }

    outer_vec.push(inner_vec.as_mut_ptr());

    unsafe {
        vec_len = outer_vec.len();
    }

    outer_vec.as_mut_ptr() as usize
}
```

output:
The issue lies in how you are trying to return a `Vec<Vec<i32>>` from your `calc_vector_in_vector()` function. In your current implementation, you are storing the address of the inner vector using `inner_vec.as_mut_ptr()` and adding it to the outer vector using `outer_vec.push(inner_vec.as_mut_ptr())`. This approach is incorrect because the inner vector will be deallocated after the function call, and you will be left with invalid addresses.

To correctly return a `Vec<Vec<i32>>`, you can make use of the `lazy_static` crate to initialize a static vector wrapped in a `Mutex` (to allow for modification later on). Additionally, you can define two static variables, `LEN_VEC` and `SIZE_INNER_VEC`, to represent the length of the outer vector and the size of each inner vector respectively.

Here's an updated solution:

```rust
static mut LEN_VEC: usize = 0;
static mut SIZE_INNER_VEC: usize = 0;

lazy_static! {
    // Wrap the vector in a Mutex to allow for modification later on
    static ref ARRAY: Mutex<Vec<i32>> = Mutex::new(vec![]);
}

pub fn calc_vector_in_vector() -> usize {
    // Set the values of LEN_VEC and SIZE_INNER_VEC

    ARRAY.lock().unwrap().as_mut_ptr() as usize
}
```

With this solution, you can now access the address of the `Vec<i32>` by calling `ARRAY.lock().unwrap().as_mut_ptr() as usize`. In JavaScript, you can use the values of `LEN_VEC` and `SIZE_INNER_VEC` to recreate the vectors within the outer vector.

Note: Make sure to properly initialize and modify the static variables `LEN_VEC` and `SIZE_INNER_VEC` before calling the `calc_vector_in_vector()` function to ensure correct behavior.

