To design a web-based chat application using Node.js, Socket.IO, and React, follow these steps:

1. Set up the project structure

Create a new directory for your project and navigate to it in your terminal.

```
mkdir chat-app
cd chat-app
```

Initialize a new Node.js project by running `npm init -y`. This will create a `package.json` file with default settings.

2. Install dependencies

Install the necessary dependencies for the project: Express, Socket.IO, and React.

```
npm install express socket.io
npx create-react-app client
```

This will set up an Express server and Socket.IO on the backend, and create a new React app in the 'client' folder for the frontend.

3. Set up the server

Create a new file called `server.js` in the root of your project directory.

```javascript
// server.js
const express = require('express');
const http = require('http');
const socketIO = require('socket.io');

const app = express();
const server = http.createServer(app);
const io = socketIO(server);

app.use(express.static('client/build'));

io.on('connection', (socket) => {
  console.log('User connected');

  socket.on('joinRoom', ({ username, room }) => {
    // Handle user joining a room
  });

  socket.on('sendMessage', (message) => {
    // Handle sending messages
  });

  socket.on('disconnect', () => {
    console.log('User disconnected');
  });
});

const PORT = process.env.PORT || 5000;
server.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`));
```

4. Set up the React frontend

Navigate to the 'client' folder and open the `src` folder. Create a new folder called 'components' and inside that folder, create two files: `Chat.js` and `Chat.css`.

In `Chat.js`, create a new React component for the chat interface.

```javascript
// client/src/components/Chat.js
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import io from 'socket.io-client';
import './Chat.css';

const socket = io.connect('/');

function Chat() {
  const [username, setUsername] = useState('');
  const [room, setRoom] = useState('');
  const [message, setMessage] = useState('');
  const [messages, setMessages] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    socket.on('message', (msg) => {
      setMessages([...messages, msg]);
    });
  }, [messages]);

  const joinRoom = () => {
    if (username && room) {
      socket.emit('joinRoom', { username, room });
    }
  };

  const sendMessage = (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    if (message) {
      socket.emit('sendMessage', message);
      setMessage('');
    }
  };

  return (
    <div className="chat-container">
      {/* Add your chat UI elements here */}
    </div>
  );
}

export default Chat;
```

Now, import this Chat component into the main `App.js` file and replace the existing content with it.

```javascript
// client/src/App.js
import React from 'react';
import './App.css';
import Chat from './components/Chat';

function App() {
  return (
    <div className="App">
      <Chat />
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

5. Implement the chat functionality

Update the server-side code in `server.js` to handle user joining a room and sending messages.

```javascript
// server.js
// ...
io.on('connection', (socket) => {
  console.log('User connected');

  socket.on('joinRoom', ({ username, room }) => {
    socket.join(room);
    socket.emit('message', { user: 'admin', text: `${username}, welcome to the room ${room}` });
    socket.broadcast.to(room).emit('message', { user: 'admin', text: `${username} has joined!` });
  });

  socket.on('sendMessage', (message) => {
    const { room } = socket.handshake.query;
    io.to(room).emit('message', { user: socket.id, text: message });
  });

  socket.on('disconnect', () => {
    console.log('User disconnected');
  });
});
// ...
```

Update the `Chat.js` component to display messages and handle user input.

```javascript
// client/src/components/Chat.js
// ...
return (
  <div className="chat-container">
    <h1>Join a chat room</h1>
    <input
      type="text"
      placeholder="Username"
      value={username}
      onChange={(e) => setUsername(e.target.value)}
    />
    <input
      type="text"
      placeholder="Room"
      value={room}
      onChange={(e) => setRoom(e.target.value)}
    />
    <button onClick={joinRoom}>Join</button>

    <div className="messages">
      {messages.map((msg, i) => (
        <div key={i}>
          <strong>{msg.user}: </strong>
          {msg.text}
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <form onSubmit={sendMessage}>
      <input
        type="text"
        placeholder="Type your message..."
        value={message}
        onChange={(e) => setMessage(e.target.value)}
      />
      <button type="submit">Send</button>
    </form>
  </div>
);
// ...
```

6. Add styles

Create some basic styling for the chat interface in `Chat.css`.

```css
/* client/src/components/Chat.css */
.chat-container {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  align-items: center;
}

input,
button {
  margin: 5px;
}

.messages {
  width: 50%;
  height: 300px;
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
  overflow-y: scroll;
  padding: 10px;
  margin-bottom: 10px;
}
```

7. Run the application

Start your server by running `node server.js` in the root of your project directory.

In a separate terminal, navigate to the 'client' folder and run `npm start` to start the React development server.

Now you should be able to access the chat application at `http://localhost:3000`. Users can join rooms, send messages, and see messages from other users in real-time.

Here's the TypeScript program that meets your requirements:

```typescript
interface User {
  name: string;
  age: number;
  location: string;
}

function getGreetingMessage(user: User) {
  const { name, age } = user;
  const timeOfDayMessage = getTimeOfDayMessage(user.location);
  return `${timeOfDayMessage}, ${name}! You're ${age} years old and currently in ${user.location}.`;
}

function getTimeOfDayMessage(location: string) {
  const currentTime = new Date();
  const hour = currentTime.getHours();

  if (hour >= 5 && hour < 12) {
    return `Good morning`;
  } else if (hour >= 12 && hour < 18) {
    return `Good afternoon`;
  } else if (hour >= 18 || hour < 5) {
    return `Good evening`;
  }

  return `Hello`;
}

const user: User = {
  name: 'John',
  age: 32,
  location: 'New York City'
};

console.log(getGreetingMessage(user));
```

This program defines an interface `User` with three required properties: `name`, `age`, and `location`. It also defines a function `getGreetingMessage` that takes a `User` object as an argument and returns a formatted message that includes the user's name, age, and location. The function calls a separate function `getTimeOfDayMessage` to generate a unique message based on the user's location and the current time of day.

The `getTimeOfDayMessage` function uses the `getHours()` method of a `Date` object to get the current hour, and then returns a different message depending on whether the hour is in the morning, afternoon, or evening.

Finally, the program creates a `User` object with some sample data and logs the output of `getGreetingMessage` to the console. The output should be similar to "Good morning, John! You're 32 years old and currently in New York City." depending on the current time.

