Based on the provided code and the issue mentioned, it seems that the interrupt is causing the kernel to crash. The `exception_handler` function is intended to handle the interrupt, but it is not being executed.

The issue might be related to the initialization of the Global Descriptor Table (GDT). The `GDT_OFFSET_KERNEL_CODE` value is set to `0x01 * 0x08`, which is used as the kernel code segment selector in the IDT entries. However, it is mentioned that this value is only used for testing purposes.

To fix this issue, you need to properly initialize the GDT with the correct segment selectors for the kernel code and data segments. Once the GDT is correctly initialized, the `GDT_OFFSET_KERNEL_CODE` value can be updated accordingly.

Here is an example of how you can initialize the GDT:

```cpp
// Initialize the GDT
void gdt_init() {
    gdt_desc_t gdt[3];  // Create an array of GDT entries

    // Null segment descriptor (index 0)
    gdt[0] = (gdt_desc_t){0};

    // Kernel code segment descriptor (index 1)
    gdt[1] = (gdt_desc_t){
        .limit_low = 0xFFFF,
        .base_low = 0x0000,
        .base_mid = 0x00,
        .access = 0x9A,  // Present, Ring 0, Code Segment
        .flags = 0xCF,   // Granularity (4KB), 32-bit Mode
        .base_high = 0x00
    };

    // Kernel data segment descriptor (index 2)
    gdt[2] = (gdt_desc_t){
        .limit_low = 0xFFFF,
        .base_low = 0x0000,
        .base_mid = 0x00,
        .access = 0x92,  // Present, Ring 0, Data Segment
        .flags = 0xCF,   // Granularity (4KB), 32-bit Mode
        .base_high = 0x00
    };

    // Load the GDT
    gdt_ptr_t gdt_ptr = {
        .limit = sizeof(gdt) - 1,
        .base = (uintptr_t)&gdt[0]
    };

    __asm__ volatile("lgdt %0" : : "m"(gdt_ptr));

    // Set the segment registers
    __asm__ volatile(
        "movw $0x10, %ax \n\t"
        "movw %ax, %ds \n\t"
        "movw %ax, %es \n\t"
        "movw %ax, %fs \n\t"
        "movw %ax, %gs \n\t"
        "movw %ax, %ss \n\t"
        "ljmp $0x08, $flush_segments \n\t"
        "flush_segments: \n\t"
    );
}
```

You can call the `gdt_init` function before initializing the IDT in the `idt_init` function. This will ensure that the GDT is properly set up before setting the kernel code segment selector in the IDT entries.

Once you have updated the GDT initialization, you can test if the interrupt is properly handled by removing the `__asm__ volatile("sti");` instruction. If the interrupt is still not handled correctly, you may need to further investigate the `exception_handler` function and the code flow.

